04905nam a22007215i 9781501757563DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017575637 a10.1515/97815017575632doi  a(DE-B1597)572381  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aLB3067.7.S65.E85 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a371.8211 aEwing, E. Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeparate Schools :bGender, Policy, and Practice in Postwar Soviet Education /cE. Thomas Ewing. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (418 p.) :b16 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures List -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION Why Single-Sex Schooling? -- tCHAPTER 1 Disciplining Gender-Making the Case for Separate Schools -- tCHAPTER 2 Teaching and Learning in Separate Schools -- tCHAPTER 3 Clean, Warm, and Calm-Girls' Schools in Action -- tCHAPTER 4 The Problem of Order-Boys' Schools in Crisis -- tCHAPTER 5 Debating Policy-The Challenge to Separate Education -- tCHAPTER 6 Restoring Coeducation-The End of an Experiment -- tCONCLUSION Learning Lessons from Soviet Separate Schools -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStarting in 1943, millions of children were separated into boys' and girls' schools in cities across the Soviet Union. The government sought to reinforce gender roles in a wartime context and to strengthen discipline and order by separating boys and girls into different classrooms. The program was a failure. Discipline further deteriorated in boys' schools, and despite intentions to keep the education equal, girls' schools experienced increased perceptions of academic inferiority, particularly in the subjects of math and science. The restoration of coeducation in 1954 demonstrated the power of public opinion, even in a dictatorship, to influence school policies. In the first full-length study of the program, Ewing examines this large-scale experiment across the full cycle of deliberating, advocating, implementing, experiencing, criticizing, and finally repudiating separate schools. Looking at the encounters of pupils in classrooms, policy objectives of communist leaders, and growing opposition to separate schools among teachers and parents, Ewing provides new insights into the last decade of Stalin's dictatorship. A comparative analysis of the Soviet case with recent efforts in the United States and elsewhere raises important questions. Based on extensive research that includes the archives of Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan, Separate Schools will appeal to historians of Russia, those interested in comparative education and educational history, and specialists in gender studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEducation and statezSoviet Union. 0aSex differences in educationzSoviet Union. 0aSingle-sex schoolszSoviet UnionxHistory. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aSoviet Union separate education 1943, Soviet Union boys’ and girls’ schools, Soviet Union coeducation 1954, popular opinion during dictatorship, last decade of Stalin's dictatorship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175756340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501757563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501757563.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA